< Text>
Maybe they're new and still tweaking things, but I've had better. Pork tacos were dry, sauce-less, and tasteless. $3 chips & salsa were a big pile of cold, Costco chips and 1/3 cup (the cooking size, the serving cup had barely anything in it) of Pace picante sauce that I already had the *exact same thing at home.* Burrito was mostly rice and sauce, very little of anything else, it wasn't safe-temperature hot or grilled very long, and the tortilla was tough. No website and difficult to find the menu on some social media platforms, but at least the menu doesn't have a million things on it (Paradox of Choice-effect). It was ready fast and it has a good location, but other than that, nothing to write home about so far.<//Text>

<Date>1603917542694</Date><username>Ubaldo Morales< /username>< Review>
Being a vegetarian I've visited Rico's Taqueria twice to purchase a veggie burrito and their enchiladas.

Rico's food has been excellent!!

I'm a Cuban and not an expert on Mexican food, but I can surely insure you that Rico's food is "Rico" "Sabroso" and priced right.

The two other Mexican food establishments in Paradise need to be aware because Rico's is going to take over this town.

I highly recommend Rico's. Located where Celestino's once stood on Skyway. Give this local business your patronage.< /Review>

<UserId.>115594659899883495354<//UserId.><gmapID>0x809cd5157d9a3a37:0xde937c38b2bd42fd</gmapID><username>Matt Sutter< /username>< date>

<Text>Brand new place and I really enjoyed the good. I picked up a pork burrito for lunch. I'm used to either a Chile Verde or carnitas when I order pork at Mexican joints, but this was different in a very good way. It must be a dry rub of some kind. Or something like that. It was a way of seasoning and preparing the pork I simply hadn't had before and I really liked it.

I can be super picky about food and they indulged all of my requests. The young man behind the counter was working really hard to get everyone's order right, and act as translator for the ladies that were cooking, and he made sure my food was made exactly as I like.

Place is starting to get a good reputation in town and it's deserved. I'm super stoked to see a new restaurant opening in town. Will definitely come back.<//Text>< pics>

<name>rae rae</name>< Review>
We drove up 30 minutes to try this place out because of the reviews. What we encountered was a bit different than others reviewed. First we checked out the menu, which was different from the one we saw here on Google reviews, their prices definently went up but they have a larger menu now. We were told it would be a 20 minute wait, it looked like there were only two employees there tonight, so thats understandable and not the reason I rated 4 stars. Ordered cheese nachos and added refried beans for one kid (4.99 plus a dollar for beans), this turned out as store bought chips and hotdogs stand cheese sauce. The refried beans were good tho. Next kid got a cheese quesadilla for 4.99. This wasn't bad, tons of cheese on a massive tortilla. Husband ordered a heart attack burrito for 10.99 it was beyond massive worth the price on that alone, however it was super greasy on top and extremely dry insides, that was an overall "meh". I ordered the street tacos with beans and rice on the side, these were very good, I was a tad disappointed at the amount of beans and rice, however, the amount of meat I got on the tacos was well over what was needed, haha, so meh...kind of a disappointing experience, If I drive through I would try it again, but I won't be driving just for this place again.  Hope this helps!<//Review>

<Rating>4< /Rating>< text>
Giant sequoias and California redwoods (also called coast redwoods) are nature's skyscrapers. These enormous trees exist primarily in Northern California, Oregon and Washington and though they have a number of common characteristics, including distinctive cinnamon-red bark, they are different

visit redwood grove park and enjoy the shade of the redwoods and the fresh green of their branches, as their height is spectacular.

It is a small but very cozy place, the only thing I do not like is that most people do not wear masks to protect themselves and to protect others.  I feel that we still need to be taking care of ourselves, even if you are vaccinated you must protect yourself. If you want to visit it, take your mask for safety.

It's fairly small but still worth seeing. The trail to the redwood is very easy. The path is fairly wide. The trail is dog friendly. Definitely recommend leaving your dog on leash since there are plenty of cyclists on the same trail. The trail is easy enough for young kids as well. Stroller accessible for the most part, although I'd recommend using the sports stroller.<//Text>

It's a great place to see redwoods rarely found in SoCal.  A nice place to walk if it's not too hot. < userid>

<Name>Mike Cousimano< /Name><time>1552775124583</time>< Rating>
5</Rating>
< Review>
Awesome little paradise of redwoods in southern california! Easy access park at carbon canyon for 7 bucks. The trail id say is a mile behind park. 30 min hike time. Make aure you stay to the right so you do not take a trail that veres off in the park. This trail will lead you to a grove of redwoods. Lots of different birds small animals and reports of mountain lion. Fun for a date hike, bringing the family, scout adventure, and so on. Id say the hike difficulty level is only a 1/10. Dogs are allowed on leash and i believe park is open from 7am-5pm<//Review>

<Pics>None< /Pics><text>My friend suggested we try El Salvadoran tamales and oh what a wonderful experience! We sat outside. The place was full of people who seemed to be Salvadoran, a very good sign.

The lady I assume to be Xina was warm, calm, kind, and unflappable. She made me feel like her only customer while the room was packed with people.

Sitting in the sun outside to eat the tamales, she served us in the same manner as inside, warm, calm, kind, and unflappable. And the tamales were beyond incredible! I'm already hooked on Mexican tamales. These were entirely different in texture, seasoning and in taste and they were fabulous. The vegetable was mixed into the masa harina dough and the beans were a paste inside. Sorry those of you used to this presentation thinking, "Duh!", but it was all new and exciting for me. The price is right too. Where are 10 stars when you need them?< /text>< response>

<Time>1388436562625< /Time><rate>4</rate><Review>Some of the reviews below are certainly outdated. I was in LA two weeks ago and the service was outstanding. I called them after I landed to pick up a car, not only did the person on the phone go through a number of choices and prices, they were running a sale for the weekend. I got a nice Mustang GT convertible for the day (originally), paperwork took a few minutes, because they didn't take any information over the phone. Outside of that, they had the car ready to go, total time was about 15 minutes at the store. The girl that helped me walked around and pointed at the minor blemishes and marked them on the paper. On Sunday, I needed the car for another day, so I called them at 10am, and requested to extend my rental, they had no issues doing so and kept the sale rate for the second day. I didn't even have to go resign any additional paperwork, what a convenience! Returning the car was also a breeze! They offer pickup and drop off to my hotel so don't even have to worry about taking a cab there. I have an office nearby and will certainly rent from them again even though there is another car rental in my hotel! Only reason I left off one star is that the car's exterior could've been kept a little cleaner, it was probably hibernating since 60 is "cooler" in CA, I had come there from 30 degrees in NYC so I can understand. Also - they close at 5pm on Saturday, which isn't bad, but the gated lot prevented me from taking the keys and coming back later for the car since my friends were waiting to go out (however, I would have a gated lot too if I kept such nice cars)! Thanks Midway - I'll see you again soon.< /Review>< Pics>

< text>
Absolutely amazing beer at this place, we went for their 3rd year anniversary and they had so many ppl and it was just great company. It was my first time here but definitely worth multiple visits. They had live music, catered food and amazing beers. I had their sampler and got to try 12 beers! So good! But I have to say their trailblazer is the best! Well if you like dark beer. But if you like light beer their guava beer is soooo good! It tastes like lemon/guava beer man I love that one to! If I had to summarize this place I would say its simple, a hidden gem and definitely worth multiple visits. If they keep up the great work I will certainly return!<//text>

< Review>
I wanted to try this place about a year ago and when I chatted with a few guys at another restaurant (Los Domingos!), I was told that on Thursday nights at 7pm, they do trivia night "Geeks Who Drink" and so I went there to taste the brews and play and had a great time with the people there....very friendly and somewhat hip.  My favorite: the Imperial IPA.  Will definitely do another visit and will bring a friend.</Review>

< user>
115597319946470164119<//user>
< text>
Must go place for beer lovers!  DON'T THINK, GO!

The Hefewiese was the best American made I have had many Hefe's from breweries from Coast to Coast try this and they have all failed to capture that Bavarian essence.  Reminds me of a Ayinger Beer I love.

I'm a hop head and their IPA'S are killer.  From nose to finish they are very satisfying.

Most tap rooms  have there standard pablum offerings for the cross over crowd/market.  This is not the case here after having many offerings of the 13-14 brew in house and on tap. All beers are above average to great.

The tasting room is as tasteful and cozy as any tap room I've visited in my travels across  America.

The family of Brewers are very hospitable and appreciate their customers.< /text>

My favorite hiking spot! There are different trails of various difficulty level. One sees a lot of wild life here.
On weekends finding a parking spot can be difficult  7:30 am onwards. There is plenty of parking, though. Sometimes I go back and park on Cristo Rey drive and hike a mile (on a trail) to the Preserve which isn't a big deal.
Beautiful wild flowers in spring and, if the winters bless us with good rain, a pretty creek to throw pebbles in.<//Review>

<user_id>113727516144543155355< /user_id><Response>None</Response>< review>
This is THE place for getting a good exercise by hiking! The wildcat loop trail has a very good elevation and is absolutely gorgeous! I totally reccommend this trail! The vista point was beautiful too! This reserve has many one-way trails due to the pandemic and they are very comfortable to be explored ðŸ˜Œ If you have pooches that are adventurous, then this reserve is not for them since dogs are not allowed. But it is amazing for us, humans, to get a fresh start here! The weekends are very busy though, so I reccommend coming earlier in the morning to get a parking spot! It's great for kids too, especially since they can be engaged with picnic tables that are everywhere for quick snacks and also because of the wild turkeys, deer and the cute animals in the farm located in the reserve! I also recommend you to take lots of water and snacks to stay hydrated â˜ºï¸â˜ºï¸</review>

Nice place to hike albeit a little long at 8+ miles if you take the high meadow trail. Lots of crowd especially in the weekends and parking gets full pretty soon. Views are not exhilarating but there are a few points to lookout for. Restrooms only near the parking lot as expected so plan accordingly. Trail is moderate and can be done by beginners as well. < Rating>
5<//Rating>
<Review>This place paints a different picture, answers my different call and brings a certain comfort for me each time I need to get away from the chaos of urban living, stressful work weeks and noisy busy streets.

Though a popular spacious place and often filled with floods of people on the weekends, this space has a variety of offerings--lush greens, wandering animals, beautiful meadows, bubbling creeks, leisure paved paths and higher trails that lead to more quietude for those that crave for moments of peace and meditation.

If you're intentional about seeking out some solitude to clear your mind, listen to the sound of nature and spend a little time in contemplation while admiring God's creation right in your South Bay backyard, this place just may be a sweet gem you need without committing to a long drive--it's easily accessible and a quick ride from most of local neighborhoods.</Review>< pictures>

<username>Amy C< /username><text>My favorite place to go hiking. There are multiple trails to choose from with great views of the Bay Area. If you go early in the morning, you're more likely to catch deer grazing. There's also a lot of wild turkeys. When it's hot out, be careful of rattle snakes sunbathing in the middle of the trail. Due to the rainy season, there's been quite a spectacular bloom of wildflowers. There are nice restrooms in the two parking lots closest to the trails and a restroom by the farm. On a good weather weekend, you'll need to come early, otherwise, expect budgeting time to hunt/wait in line for a parking spot.< /text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNitARtoy-LNdAFjsc6LfbWVGvG0jJdCzknR64c=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOFQ9HDY3dHkhnbEWl5MkUGGdsjjcgd2vHevnKW=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMOu6Rn9snmscg78_6-tZIlIlOFc1unmvqFnGin=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNe8NrJnnhfjyZFocfV_4MMLBF4_Fd-YsN1rROp=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO5OFOguKVuckUeAVkBJDB0krC1TwUv686kbOti=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOCmhcjujhKT0B6xbKlLDSifMybLY69fZ-sm8cx=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPyVAj8pdeNEHNz9OWm5LjCAYDSJ6-bpSI7M07N=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM71hqreYnUeRBoIJM76s2ckABL0quAoWOHv8QS=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOIyOFGZMiCs30hlto0UmmVYZND188lPYxwoB4q=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics><rate>5< /rate>< gmapID>

<Response>None< /Response><Review>This is an amazing getaway right in the middle of bay area. Very easily accessible from South Bay and is hugely popular among locals. This is not a local city park, it's a natural preserve and stretches across the santa Cruz mountains and is gone to local flora and fauna, including the elusive mountain lions.

The park has many trails and thus doesn't bore you even if you are a regular. If your are training for a marathon, this is the ideal place as it has mostly shaded trails with fair amount of elevation gain. Kids are welcome and you will do many of them. Bikers are welcome too and is a great opportunity to get some mountain biking training done here.

There is also a petting farm located about a mile from the parking lot and is fin with kids. They have goats, sheep and cows.

Make sure to get early as the parking lot gets full very quickly. Or get in later when the earlier ones are leaving.< /Review><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNiCfXgAF1cN-4AQZnl_Nzyf59Fv7HlT-De31ZP=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOImHHrfZAF4AE5ak3Y7bpB9KsZY5TfOoZLeKtu=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPzFfh2VCVYxHxu8EdQ9YoVrHG6ErwR5SIZ_L_e=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO6MYGaLvpjbtuj0CWL_0uIggGsVHTDjm4PqfWN=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPEch5pwOgp1YB51MwX7wT3oMItNpQSBhpep3C2=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNKzlMxVHvM1xQ58zNN4QhBRasZPGP80dXgqwHR=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPWUm3MmvY1wPdS5JPuzZMLGTo5j0U2N0bM4-Ap=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPznYRq8rgHM7dOQohG_qsOQ3DT4Lo3Lq6ZTKKf=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPJxtRA8qYoCT3SNssIgwMYE6A_lrwPs-0fKXqX=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNV3UhQ2HNH9i5RYpvaA2xyvhBcH7gS5T7wBBG2=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOcV1bt72RUvHVuZ0W0j8HPUVPo4x_fl2d7GZAh=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNVQM3ZkX5pyv9Z1figTdManbvpKTiMVKUDv2-z=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPv5XaMTOONBrwQ-6PlS6pjRnSe9gjzeYhQQihX=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP1t--XBTS2qT1C4Xj-awC6XHOW8JK4g0kgM_0I=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMtbnLvYRBWZ6mG2NxcvgF0CxkQK_NSMXGE4Pe5=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPM7Ra8Skt7vZnb2VaftDiWw3gBzfL7wj7-iKas=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pics></record>

Large nature area with over 20 trail of various difficulties. Scenic with wild turkeys and deer. Great for family or seasoned solo hikers. Benches around for relaxing sits and some picnic tables for groups. Paved road for walking makes for easy treks for those of us with a bad ankle or knee. So close to home right off I280. Remember to bring water and enjoy nature.< /review>

<text>Something for everyone here.  Need a easy walk with a stroller? Yes.  Need a long climb for your Grand Canyon prep? That too.  Just want to hang out with the kids and chicks (young goats and chickens...) at the farm? Sure.

The parking is lots better since the second lot was remodeled.  If you're thinking of biking, there's a totally different route (not hilly or car-y) for you through the neighborhood in the other side of 280, it's very convenient.< /text>< Pictures>

<userid>100342707144994636717</userid>< username>
Ganesh B< /username>
<Time>1588492434415< /Time>< rating>
5< /rating>
< Text>
Awesome workout place for different levels of fitness and training--from an almost flat 2 mile round trip to the Deer Hollow farm, to a moderate (550+ ft climb) 3 mile closed loop hike/run along Coyote trail (my favorite), to a difficult (1600+ ft climb) 9 mile closed loop hike/run along the PG&E trail.

There is a lot of parking, but this place is extremely crowded during weekends and holidays. Be prepared to wait up to 15-45 min to get parking during busy time. Definitely advise car-pooling if coming here with friends and family. Consider the 'waiting for parking' as a meditation exercise before your workout!ðŸ˜ƒ

Now the best part! This place has awesome trails (especially when various streams have water running), lots of wildlife (birds, snakes, wild turkeys, deers, rabbits, and occasionally mountain lions), and multiple restrooms. The CA park rangers here are always vigilant, and helpful when needed.

The Deer hollow farm is a nice stop for small children if your are here for a casual visit. Updating (3/7/2020) with pictures from the farm (1-2 day old baby goats, and wild tom turkeys performing mating dance).

Update: May 03, 2020. Today we spotted a great blue heron in the preserve. It has been several years since we last spotted them here.<//Text>

< UserId.>
107979944693520343976<//UserId.>
<Name>Sumant Singh< /Name><date>1548700314889<//date>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< text>
Awesome trails for all types of runners, hikers. Steep hills for gruesome LT workout, downhill well paved trails for constant low impact form work.
Been there twice for trail running/ hiking, no complaints, restrooms are quite well maintained too.
It gets dark in some areas of the trails due to trees so make sure you check sunset time before starting your hike/ run.
Climbed 1600, still so much more to go.

Starting at PG&E is better in my opinion as there are more gravel sections which are easier for uphill. Coming down on Coyote is better due to more smooth downhill and no gravel.

Lookout for small tree roots sticking out in the trails, they can be deceivingly high, I tripped on one coming downhill, not a pleasant experience.<//text>

<user_id>118215131078655072321</user_id>< Name>
Kalim Moghul< /Name>
<time>1595441718460< /time><rate>5< /rate>< review>
Beautiful views and fairly well maintained trails make this a great place for hiking or biking. There's a modestly sized flying field for radio control airplanes and the like. Parking is plentiful, though it got a bit crowded later in the afternoon. Social distancing was not difficult and mask discipline was fairly good if not perfect. Narrower trails have been marked one way to promote distancing, so it's a good idea to consult the map posted at the trail head.<//review>

< review>
There are many good short hikes here, and at some view points you can see a view of the south bay and peninsula.  You can also do longer hikes up black mountain, to Rhus ridge or Hidden Villa.  There is a good mix of trails with varied terrain.  Scenery are green after rain, but otherwise some parts are quite yellow in the summer and fall.< /review>

< review>
Lovely easy nature paths with a sweet creek next to the walking.  Well maintained and my favorite,  the petting zoo after a reasonable over one mile walk. Animals are well cared for,  a very kind docent that was very happy to explain that area and the history. WHAT MYSTIFIED me were the 3 dead wild turkeys we encountered driving away from the place, in the open field across the street from the park. There's bike paths with various levels of difficulty as well as other paths for walking.< /review>

<Time>1554140538257< /Time>< rate>
5< /rate>
< Review>
Deer Hollow farm loop trail is an easy trail, where the trail paths are well constructed roads. you can take your children along ,and they can ride their scooters as well.
There is a nice ranch created at the end of the trail. The ranch has sheeps ,goats ,baby lambs, turkeys,cows and pigs.
There is a small museum near the Deer Hollow farms , the museum has display of stuffed and preserved animals including red fox, owls, eagles , mountain lions and many more. You will also enjoy the touch table with bones, feathers, leaves,  seeds , fur ,nests and more</Review>
</record>
</dataset><record>
<text>Love this park. Great trail runnning there. Get there early on the weekends! Gets packed very quickly. Also, try the Coyote Creek trail as an alternative to the more popular PG&E trail. Here's a photo I took from top of PG&E trail.</text>< gmapID>

<user>109355248233785091780<//user><Name>Ryan Jordan</Name>< Time>
1551455482654</Time>
<Rate>5</Rate>< Review>
Open free to the public 365 days a year. Open 30 mins before sunrise to 30 mins after sunset.

No dogs allowed.
Helmets required for bikes/scooters/etc (even for adults).
No drones allowed. Fix winged RC aircraft allowed at the runway. (Located near the main entrance).

Parking is competitive on the weekends, easier on week days.

Some beautiful trails, the deeper you go in the less people you encounter.</Review>

< Text>
This is my favorite place for hiking especially in feb-apr. The creek is flowing and I love it.
There are couple of trails. Also there is a farm which is an attraction for little kids. Usually takes about 1:30 -2 hrs for wild cat loop hike. There are longer hikes available too.
Parking is not exactly limited but it is favorite spot so its hard to find parking no matter what time of day you go.</Text>

< review>
Good place to visit for trail lovers, be careful while bringing your children as during summer time you can see snakes near the grass/bushy places. Also there are warning of mountain lion. As we trail we have seen deers and also some creepy sounds inside the forest. Really must try place. But please bring water to keep yourself hydrated.< /review>

<Rate>5</Rate>< review>
This is a great place to hike, bike or run trails. There are trails for every level. Plenty of parking spots with three parking lots. Water fountains are at the Equestrian Parking Lot and the main parking lot at the bottom of the entrance road. It opens earliest in the Summer at 5:30 am depending on the month. It closes at Sunset. My favorite trails are Coyote Trail, Upper Wildcat Loop, Black Mountain Trail, High Meadow Trail and Stephen Arbors Trail which most locals know as PG & E Trail.< /review>

This is a go to hiking place if you live in Cupertino, Saratoga and near by areas. There are plenty of trails here. Place is generally busy. Even though there are lot of parking, it can be hard to find parking in the mornings, since it  is a extremely popular hiking spot. PG&E trail is one of the popular trails. You can bring children to show farm animals, there is a picnic area near the farm as well. Great place to visit if you are a hiking enthusiast.<//text>

<username>Jubin Edachery</username>< Review>
Great place to connect with nature and farm life. Park close to the 280 bridge, and walk in to a system of small stroller friendly hikes leading to a farm with goats, chicken and other animals - that kids would love. There is a small picnic area too (restrooms are smelly).
If you want a more strenuous hike, there are trails that lead all the way up the mountain (or around it) and provides some good views from the top.<//Review>

This is perfect place for walking, running, cycling, picnic or drone flying. They have spearate path for cyclers at many places. The area is huge and connects more then 10-20 trails. They have barn also inside which was a nice surprise for us. There are multiple places for picnic too. They have 3 parking lots, the first and second one are small but the last parking lot at the bottom is big. They have drone flying zone near first and second parking lot. <name>Indra Singhal<//name>< review>
This preserve and the trails were my regular weekly haunt years ago. Went back to see how it's changed - 7:40 am on a Sunday morning - and i found the lower parking lot completely full. Saw a few cars occupying two slots, now that's on them.

This preserve has a variety of trails - there is one that will match your own desire for level of activity. From the parking lot, you can tell this is a very popular place - so if you like walking with lots of people, kids, babies in strollers, joggers, this is the place to be! If not, there are hundreds of trails in dozens of open space preserves in the south bay...<//review>

<Text>My favorite place for trail running near Mountain View. Rancho has miles of well-maintained trails, all marked with signs to keep you going in the right direction. You'll get to see a variety of plant and animal life here, from bay trees to California thrashers. Keep an eye out for interesting mushrooms, too. Got kids? They'll love the working farm, which keeps chickens, goats, and pigs. Parking can be difficult, especially on weekend mornings.< /Text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><resp>None< /resp>< Gmap_id>

The place is great for a day hike or a morning run to the top of the mountain. The first 3km are pretty flat. After that is all uphill. Trees become more scarce half way to the top so is a good idea to wear susncreen and glasses. Parking gets very crowded very early in the morning during weekends. If you want to make sure to find parking arrive before 6am. Bathrooms are located in the parking lot and water fountains are available. There is also a small farm where you can buy organic eggs and other vegetables.</review>

< UserId.>
116391680725324254315<//UserId.>
<name>Mandi W</name><time>1566758894544<//time><rating>5</rating>< review>
I really enjoy this trail. Easy to get to. Lots of parking. Good trails. Not a ton of people.

Let's start from the beginning. Parking. This reserve has a lot of full sun areas so most people are here before 9am on weekends. They have multiple lots, but the bottom most lot is the largest and is closest to the reserve entrance and bathrooms. The closer to 9am you get there, the harder it'll be to find a spot.

As for the trails itself, wear trail running shoes or sneakers you're okay with getting dirty. It's all dirt paths. Also watch out for horse poop.

Bikers are allowed in parts but dogs are not. Parking is also free.

They have bike lanes but they're not labeled well so everyone just walks wherever. It's never been a problem when I've been there though because the paths are wide.

As for the trails itself. There's a lot of shorter ones that when combined, become longer hikes. We've always gone to the lookout points so you get a 4 mile uphill climb to about 1000ft, then 4 miles back down. You can combine some so they're 11-13 miles if you want something longer or more difficult. Same with the other way around. You can stay on the flatter beginning path for an easier walk.

As for the sights, they got it going on. Lookout trails have beautiful views. Tons of nature, hills and views like the Apple donut campus, NASA building and redwood City salt mines (are they mines?... Lake?...)... They also have goats. So that's cute.

Most trails are part sun and part shade so wear breathable clothing, hats, sunglasses, and sunscreen. I've definitely seen some women wearing very little because of the heat, but they're beat red and don't even realize how burnt they are.

Trails are pretty wide for the most part. A few spots where we walk single file because of hikers coming the other way. These are not trails for strollers. If you bring one, stick to the easy flat part only, don't attempt the harder hikes because of the elevation.

They have bathrooms at the lowest level parking lot, and two portapotties further in on the flat area. No bathrooms higher up.

Overall, it's a really nice hike that's quiet and challenging but not too long. I also like that the first half is uphill while the second part is downhill. I've definitely done it the other way and that's less fun.</review>

<rating>5< /rating>< user_name>
Rhys Rookard< /user_name>
< user_id>
104757969047292171146</user_id>
<pictures>None</pictures>< Review>
I have been hiking in the Bay Area for years and Rancho San Antonio remains my #1 place to hike. They have 3 parking areas but they can fill up on weekends and holidays causing you to have to wait for people to leave. There are a number of trail options but hiking to the top via the PG&E trail gives you the best workout and the best view. The trail has a good amount of shade so even on the warmest days you will get some relief. If you hike early enough you might see some deer and wild turkeys. There are always a good number of people there so you wonâ€™t feel as though you are out in the wilderness by yourself.< /Review>

<Gmap_id>0x808fb1779c15d4d9:0xc406f4b91b86595e</Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<gmap_id>0x808fb1779c15d4d9:0xc406f4b91b86595e<//gmap_id><UserId.>112704161954465801206< /UserId.><time>1555304681457</time><user_name>Francis Li</user_name>< text>
A convenient park for elevation and distance training. Quick one-hour loops to comfortable half-day hikes. Preferable to Mission Peak for hot and cloudless days thanks to shade on many stretches of trail. The animal farm is a popular attraction (but not always open). Trails are muddy after rain. Reception is pretty solid throughout the park. Parking is free, but can be a challenge on swell days. Restrooms available at trailheads.< /text>

< review>
Popular, expansive park... great for trail running (with challenging climbs), lots of groups hiking & running... avoid weekend mornings, unless you get there pretty early... you'll be driving around a while looking for a place to park...the 5(!) parking lots fill up quickly.  Family friendly animal farm on-site, with cows, goats, ducks, and hungry chickens (which they let older kids feed).  Docents around to educate you.  Yes, cows are really huge up close...</review>

<Pictures>None< /Pictures><Time>1537046735340< /Time><Review>Great area for hiking. From the parking lot, go right for a nice level walk to the working farm. Go left for a steep uphill. At the top branch to the right for a long, gentle downward slope that goes to the farm, or continue uphill for a long hike around the entire ravine, with a couple of cutoff paths in between. From the farm, go back-left for the gentle uphill, go left for the long path up the middle of the ravine, or go right for the long path up the right side of the ravine. Lots of options, all of them good.</Review><response>None</response>< name>

<Review>It's an awesome outdoor loci where it has something for everybody. I see folks flying drones and model planes on the upper fields next to a paved parking area. As you drive down the road l, there're more parking spots; and there's a public restroom in the middle of the parking lot that I consider clean and no signs of drug use. Rangers patrol this area quite often, they're knowledgable and eager to help. There are multiple trails but every one but the Black Mountain Trail (high elevation gain) is easy. Not into hiking? No worries. There's an animal farm in the area too so everyone is welcomed!</Review>< Time>

< text>
Such a wonderful place to hike. There are flat trails that are good for strollers and more inclined trails if you want something harder. I've only gone with my baby so I've stuck with the easier hikes, but it looks like there's plenty for a real hike.

My son loves seeing the turkeys and deer wandering around.<//text>

< text>
We love this park where it has nice hiking/running trails.  It is kids friendly park where there is Deer Hallow Farm which is a petting zoo and open for everyone. There is a hiking trail of round trip around 4.6 from parking lot to the Vista point. The Vista point has a nice view looking towards south Bay.  Park is very beautiful and green, especially after the rain.</text>

<rate>5<//rate>< Review>
Very nice hiking trail with well preserved nature. Combine some trails, we can make different length and difficulty level trails. Along the trail, we can see many insects, lizards, deers and wild  turkeys.  Around farm gets a bit crowded with many children. It is nice working farm and number of farm animals out all the time. There are a few parking areas, however so many people visit the park, parking can be challenge especially on weekends.< /Review>

A great place to hike, with a nice view of the town from the top. There is a small farm at the bottom of the field, which houses sheeps, goats, hens, and rabbits. The hike has some shaded and some non- shaded areas, so it could be a little sunny on a hot day. Overall, it is a great hike!< /Review>

< Text>
This is a beautiful place for hikes, picnics, runs, bike rides with family and friends, weekends and weekdays. Hide up to Vista Point from the many trails options, and see a great view of the valley. Even SF and Oakland are visible on a clear day. You can see deer, squirrels, lizards, rabbits, snakes, turkeys, and bluejays. Bobcats and mountain lions have also been sighted. The farm is great-pigs, goats, cows, herbs, flowers. This place is on my favorites list. Parking can be hard but with patience, you can get a space.</Text>

<Response>None<//Response>< Name>
Terry Manley Sr<//Name>
< review>
Such a beautiful place I kinda hate to tell everyone how nice it is because I'd like to keep it a better secret.  If you want the perfect place to get out of the city without driving for hours this is your place.  Great clean tails with and without elevation,  some paved and some dirt.  Great for hiking, biking, picnicing and mostly relaxing.  There's a nicely mowed grass airfield with wind velocity and wind socks for flying your model planes,  helicopters or drones.  Public bathrooms are available at the beginning of the trails and more just after Deer Farm where the is a petting and viewing area of all the animals.  Parking is the only down side. And it's not terrible.  Early in the day and later in the day it's never a problem. I'm just thankful they haven't wiped away more nature to pave more parking.  If you enjoy the outdoors this is your place... but don't tell anybody else let's keep this gem a secret!<//review>

<user_id>106689967933838920220<//user_id><name>Srikumar Chari<//name><Date>1568462903676<//Date><Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
A remarkable park!! Lots of different levels of hikes, there's one for every skill level. Parking lot to farm - great for toddlers, go past farm towrds wild cat loop trail - beginners but make sure you turn back before the hills, mid level you can go up the hill but turn back before the last extremely steep hill. PGE trail (Abbors trail) - a difficult hike but even there you can turn it into a mid hike but crossing over near the first electric pole on hike, but if you continue make sure you really are used to a difficult hike. TAKE WATER!!

The views of the valley are spectacular with a lot of photo ops if you are into that.< /Review>

<Pics>None<//Pics><user_name>Daphne Pareas<//user_name><Resp>None<//Resp>< rate>
3< /rate>
< text>
It's crowded because it's so convenient. The trails are are hilly and full of people; kids on bikes or kids running around, adults walking in groups, etc. It is very hard to find parking here; Uber or bike or show up at dawn, or just go somewhere else. Deer Hollow farm is in a canyon that is 10 degrees colder than the surrounding area so bring gloves and extra layers in the winter if you get cold easily. You can usually see deer here and sometimes turkeys. There are some views of the South Bay if you hike a few miles.</text>

< review>
Loved coming here for a hike with a friend and by toddler. Great retreat away from the busy lives of the silicon valley. Can't believe it is so close to the hustle and bustle of city life. I only walked on the east route but saw so many options for those who don't have a stroller. Restrooms were clean. Parking is hard to get but I got lucky on a weekday. Spotted 20+ deers so close to us. My toddler loved seeing the sheep and goats too.</review>

< review>
Rancho San Antonio is a preserve that combines both accessibility (it is right on the border of Los Altos/Los Altos Hills) and enough miles of trails to pack in a serious hike for the day. You could hike nearly 19 miles from the main parking lot up to Black Mountain and back, or you can exit the preserve at Hidden Villa and get ferried back from Moody Road to your car. The main area, within a mile of the parking lot and the Deer Hollow farm can feel crowded on weekends, but start hiking out a mile, and you'll start to find the solitude enjoyed by most serious hikers.< /review>

< text>
Great walking trails through open and wooded areas. Deer Hollow Farm is fun and educational for young kids, with goats, sheep, cows, pigs, chickens, ducks, and geese on view. Parking is ample, but everyone wants to park in the lower lot, so if you're there during busy hours save yourself some aggravation and just park in one of the upper ones.</text>

< review>
Great place for a workout. I've been here multiple times. It can be very busy on weekends and after work. Good for a hiking workout and parts of it are good for running. There are shady spots, which is where I happen to see a few rattlesnakes, otherwise lots of areas of no shade and hot. Bring some water.</review>

<Date>1423213493477<//Date><gmapID>0x808fb1779c15d4d9:0xc406f4b91b86595e<//gmapID>< Text>
There is something for everyone here and it is just one of the many reasons this is a much better place to go than Mission Peak or Communication Hill. It is outdoors in a scenic area and the trails are well maintained. Just don't go after it rains. The trails very in length such as moderate trails like Wildcat Loop or much harder ones such as the PG&E trail. Although if you do the PG&E trail on a clear day you can see San Francisco not to mention the abundance of wildlife from deer to snakes.< /Text>

< review>
Tons of great hiking that is super convenient if you live locally! There are definitely more scenic hikes out there, but it's hard to expect too much when it's surrounded by South Bay suburban sprawl. Still, I really like hiking here, and if you're willing to take the time to go further into the hills, there are some trails where you feel like you really are getting away and out into nature. If you live nearby, check it out!</review>

<username>Eric Gavaletz<//username>< Review>
I was really surprised at how much wildlife I saw along the trail.  Humming birds, quail, rabbits, chipmunks, lizards, mice, cool blue birds, and the list goes on.  The trails are very well maintained if not a little too wide.  Plenty of room to stretch your legs, but not enough room to escape the rude groups of people who think the trail is the perfect place for loud conversations.  It also seems impossible to get away from the buzz of high tension power lines in this area.< /Review>

<Review>It is the closest open space to Sunnyvale. It has several vista points where you can see the bay area. There are many trails with different distances and difficulties.
You can hike all the way to the black mountain peak, which is 8 miles one way. You can also pick an short easy trail.
There are many runners running on the trails in the afternoon and evening. Trails are not that wide. Please always stay on right.<//Review><user_name>Lake X< /user_name>< gmap_id>

<user_name>Jay Paroline</user_name>< Review>
Awesome nature here. It's not at all uncommon to see free range turkeys, deer, quail and of course lots of ground squirrels. And the farm is sure to be a great attraction for kids, with pigs, cows, ducks and chickens.
Besides the animals, the hike up towards the farm is admittedly kind of boring, lots of open space and not a lot of trees, it can be pretty brutal on the hottest days, but once you get into the forest it's quite pleasant.< /Review>

<Text>Rancho San Antonio is a true hikerâ€™s paradise right in the center of the hustle and bustle of Silicon Valley! Itâ€™s huge, just under 4,000 acres with 24 miles of hiking trails. The Open Space Preserve supplies a detailed map of all the trails, get a paper map at trail heads or PDF on website (paper map larger). You can hike an individual trail or combine a few to form loops of various lengths. Most trails are people-only, but there are some that allow bikes and horses (I avoid those â€“ marked on map). There are 3 or 4 places where you can begin your hikes (parking can be a challenge on weekends, but weekdays are easy). I usually park at the end of Mora Drive, which gives you access to multiple trails. Trails vary in challenge. An easy beginnerâ€™s loop is the Rogue Valley trail, about 3 miles. If I want more of a challenge, the Chamise Trail is good, about 5 miles out and back and takes you through the Duveneck pasture, a quiet tranquil (400 foot elevation gain). The PG&E Trail is challenging, 4 miles with a 1,600 ft elevation gain. Wildcat Canyon is a good trail, shaded mostly, and brings you back to the Deer Hollow Farm where they keep some animals. Black Mountain is the most challenging, another 1,800 feet in elevation gain after you get to the end of the Chamise trail! Be in good hiking shape and take your time! Take lots of water with you on hot days! Donâ€™t step on the lizards! (Western Swifts are everywhere).<//Text>< Gmap_id>
0x808fb1779c15d4d9:0xc406f4b91b86595e< /Gmap_id>

<time>1386185062965< /time>< text>
Love coming here. It has something for everyone. For families, the trails are easy to run on, and on certain days there is a small farm with goats and other animals for the kids to see.

For the runners, there's enough paths where you can leave the crowd and go on to more challenging runs. They have nice vista points to reward yourself to getting the top. Parking can be tough but not impossible, it's ok to park up the hill. You're going to be walking anyways.<//text>

< user_name>
kaleem b<//user_name>
<Time>1488904303712</Time><Rating>4</Rating>< review>
What a contrast to the gridlocked concrete torture of Silicon Valley.
Only 20 minutes drive from there, u can quickly experience that  kind of arid, almost starched beauty that reflects this region well. The hike is quite easy, with a wide mostly paved pathways snaking around the hills. The views are spectacular of the mellow landscape. Shame about the obscene electric power lines... 1 star less for that.
Honestly after a dog-eat-dog binary-focused day trapped in the tentacles of whatever tech business u slave away for, this is like sinking smoothly into a lush golden bath of melodies that stroke ur soul.</review>

< UserId.>
115122118948501365043< /UserId.>
<Name>Jimmy Vales< /Name>< date>
1480229121443</date>
<Rating>5</Rating>< text>
Five stars only based on the memory I had of going to this place around 2007 - 2009. Now, yes, I do the favor of introducing people to the dizzying number of turns and intersections of this place before cutting them loose to visit on their own, but it is no longer the weekly weekend trek of the grueling PG&E trail or just to get outside for one of the quicker, easier loops. PARKING has become a stress-inducer. People have gotten ugly. I have witnessed a parking confrontation primarily due to the arrogance of one driver and nearly became involved in one myself had I arrived just seconds sooner. Throughout the years, the grounds and trails have been well maintained, though I attribute the wider trails to people not staying within the boundaries. Wildlife sightings are hit or miss, but I have seen a banded snake, a rattlesnake that was within striking distance but luckily too young to know that I was a potential threat, deer, turkey, hares, pheasants, ground squirrels, birds of flight that I'm too ignorant to identify, and my favorite: a California Newt. So, if you don't know any better, have never been, want to get outside, need to work in some cardio, like nature's creatures, then try the place out. You'll figure out when to go so actually can find a parking spot. And people of all ages are afoot on weekends, so it really is a place for a everyone - hence its popularity.</text>
<pictures>None</pictures>< response>
None< /response>

< Text>
I love hiking here, the trails are beautiful and well maintained.  However, the parking situation is awful, so few spots for the size of this park.  The wealthy neighborhood next door to the parking lot, where every house has at least a 2 car garage and a driveway, has recently instituted permit only street parking which makes the situation even more frustrating.  I pay my taxes that pave your road and ya'll have more than enough space to park your Teslas and BMWs.< /Text>

(Translated by Google) A very nice place to enjoy with the family.
You can go have a picnic, you can ride a bike, you can walk or run.

There are various animals, and various paths to choose from.

They have several parking lots but they fill up so you will walk around until you find one.

They have toilets.

The place is clean.

What I recommend is to put more garbage cans in the canine since I found several bottles of water thrown away and those harm the animals and insects of the place.

But I recommend it 100%

< text>
(Translated by Google) It is a good place to be with children. There is also a course where you can enjoy more than an hour of trail while you are pulling a stroller, and you can climb the mountain and see the Silicon Valley. There are deer farms in the middle, and there are many people who can see sheep and pigs. There is also a place where you can eat lunch in the middle, so it is a good place to take lunch and hike.
The parking lot is quite wide, but there are a lot of people, so when I arrived at 12 o'clock, it took about 10 minutes to park. At 2 o'clock there were more than 10 cars waiting. Please refer to parking time ~

(Original)

<time>1557035019143< /time>< review>
(Translated by Google) Beautiful place to walk! Lovely livestocks in Deer Hollow Farm. Great scenery at a vista point.
A pleasant place to stroll and climb. When I visited in early May, I had plenty of parking space. There were quite a few people but it was very easy to walk. The scenery is beautiful, and you can see livestock such as sheep, goats, cattle, and chickens when you visit the farm. Be sure to visit Deer Hollow Farm. It takes 20 to 30 minutes from the entrance to the farm.
Wild turkeys are easy to see. I could see wild deer or rabbit, but I could not see it. If you climb the Vista point for 30 minutes on the farm, you can see the view from Mountain View to San Jose. There are many people who come to the stroller because the road is wide and flat. The vista point on the farm is not steep, but there is a little slope and a narrow section.

(Original)
Beautiful place to walk! Lovely livestocks in Deer Hollow Farm. Great scenery at a  vista point.
